Case Study - Thera Bank: Using Logistic Regression Models for determining personal Loans Purchase¶

University of Texas at Austin - Post Graduate Program in AI and Machine Learning¶

by Rodrigo H. Correa¶

Introduction¶

This case study is designed to use supervised Machine Learning in order to determine likelihood of purchase of credit products by a bank.

The dataset comprises of data on 5000 customers, mainly relationship with the bank and purchase of products and also response to last loan campaign conducted by the bank.

3. Preparing the Dataset: train_test_split¶

Here the objective is to separate the Dataset into two partitions:

Train - Where the algorithm should learn how to predict outcomes from the model. Test - Where we will test the results and compare to real data and verify the fit.

Creating an object of feature columns = where will the model learn from¶

In here and from the first model, we are to insert every single column from the dataset, with the exception of ID (we know it is a 100% unique column with the EDA, does not make sense to insert it) and Personal Loan, for us not to predict something on itself.

In [91]:
feature_cols = ['Age', 'Experience', 'Income', 'ZIP_Code', 
                    'Family', 'CCAvg', 'Education', 'Mortgage', 
                    'Securities_Account', 'CD_Account', 'Online', 'CreditCard']

Let's then call X the subset with the feature columns

In [133]:
X = df[feature_cols]
y = df['Personal_Loan']

Then, I will create the train and test sets using train_test_split, using a 70/30 division for the dataset and creating a random state for replication purposes.

The number is 42 just as an homage to the ultimate question to life, the universe and everything; and it is quite easy to remember.

In [134]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.3, random_state=42)

5. How can we improve the model simply - A second Attempt by removing variables.¶

From the correlation matrix, we can verify that some of the columns do not seem to contribute to the model at all, such as ZIP code, Age and Experience.

Let's try the model again without those.

I am simply using the very same code with a few changes regarding feature_cols.

In [164]:
feature_cols2 = [ 'Income', 
                    'Family', 'CCAvg', 'Education', 'Mortgage', 
                    'Securities_Account', 'CD_Account', 'Online', 'CreditCard']
X2 = df[feature_cols2]
y = df['Personal_Loan']
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X2, y, test_size = 0.3, random_state=42)
#step two: fit the model into train set
model.fit(X_train, y_train)
# Step three: predict model to test set.
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
cnf_matrix = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
cnf_matrix

array([[1329,   14],
       [  65,   92]])

The confusion matrix already shows better results, with more true negatives (1329) and true positives (92) and less false positives (65) and false negatives (92)

6. Conclusion¶

According to the whole analysis on of the Dataset, it comes to a conclusion that it is quite possible to predict with a very good degree of certainty the type of client that is prone to hiring a Personal Loan: people who have hired other products and services from the bank, of higher income and that have higher average spending on Credit Card.

Whereas, variables such as age or experience seem not to count as much, in contrary to what we would expect, and therefore add to a model based on judgement.

Of course, a 0.90 accuracy for a model is not, by all means, bad; However, 0.95 (rounded) is significantly better, which in turn, can save a lot of money in terms of sales expenses and overall effort.

Thus, by creating a method that is more precise and by understanding possible "triggers" of what is credit acquiring behavior, Theras Bank can focus on approaching personal credit to services of higher likelihood of combined use, such as credit cards.

From the results, it seems that a very "plain vanilla" model such as Logistic Regression can be incredibly powerful in predicting outcomes such as these. While other more sophisticated models can be attempted, the straightforwardness of this method qualifies it for a very good standard model for first attempt by the bank and these values becoming the standard precision required of other models to surpass in order to be considered.
